NYC Taxi¶

Introduction¶

The are two main objectives in this notebook:

  • To explore the data offered by NYC about trips taken by NYC taxis
  • To develop a model that can predict the tip amount.

The data used in this notebook have been downloaded from here using March, June and November. Documentation about this data can be found here.

def non_na_percentage(df):
    """Returns the percentage of non NA values"""
    return (100*df[df.columns].count() \
                 / len(df[df.columns])).sort_values()

In [15]:
df_taxi = df_taxi[(df_taxi['extra'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['mta_tax'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['tip_amount'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['tolls_amount'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['improvement_surcharge'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['total_amount'] > 0) &
                      (df_taxi['fare_amount'] >= 0) &
                      (df_taxi['trip_distance'] > 0) &
                      (df_taxi['passenger_count'] > 0) &
                      (df_taxi['passenger_count'] < 10) &
                      (df_taxi['tpep_pickup_datetime'] != df_taxi['tpep_dropoff_datetime'])]

date_mask = df_taxi['tpep_pickup_datetime'].map(lambda x: (x.year == 2017 and (x.month == 3 or x.month == 6 or x.month == 11))) == True
df_taxi = df_taxi[date_mask]

The data has negative values and evident outliers (passenger_count) so let's clean this selecting only values that have sense. Moreover, passenger_count has a strange value: 0. This value is also avoided. Also, we should avoid trips with the same date for pickup and dropoff.

The data has dates from months we are not interested in. We should filter the dates.

In [20]:
def styled_barplot(x, title, special_x_size=8, xticks=None):
    """Plot a barplot with a custom style"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(special_x_size,4))
    ax= sns.barplot(x.index, x.values, alpha=0.8)
    
    if xticks != None:
        ax.set_xticklabels(xticks)

    plt.ylabel('# of {}'.format(title), fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(title), fontsize=12)

    rects = ax.patches
    labels = x.values
    for rect, label in zip(rects, labels):
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width()/2, height + 5, label, ha='center', va='bottom')

If we focus on the target variable (tip_amount) we discover that there are some variables with a interesting correlation: tolls_amount, RatecodeID and trip_distance. This is important for the model developed later.

Model - Predicting tip amount¶

Data Preparation¶

In [60]:
df_taxi_creditcard = df_taxi[(df_taxi['payment_type'] == 1) & (df_taxi['tip_amount'] <= 15)]
In [61]:
vendorid_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['VendorID'], prefix='vi', prefix_sep='_')
passenger_count_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['passenger_count'], prefix='pc', prefix_sep='_')
store_and_fwd_flag_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['store_and_fwd_flag'], prefix='sff', prefix_sep='_')
ratecodeid_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['RatecodeID'], prefix='rt', prefix_sep='_')
pickup_month_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['pickup_month'], prefix='pim', prefix_sep='_')
pickup_day_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['pickup_day'], prefix='pid', prefix_sep='_')
pickup_hour_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['pickup_hour'], prefix='pih', prefix_sep='_')
pickup_weekday_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_taxi_creditcard['pickup_weekday'], prefix='piw', prefix_sep='_')

df_taxi_creditcard = pd.concat([df_taxi_creditcard, vendorid_dummies, passenger_count_dummies, store_and_fwd_flag_dummies, ratecodeid_dummies,
                    pickup_month_dummies, pickup_day_dummies, pickup_hour_dummies, pickup_weekday_dummies], axis=1)
In [62]:

Document your choice of model / algorithm, discussing why you chose it over alternatives :

There are two main reasons why I have chosen XGBoost: the perfomance it offers and the execution speed.

XGBoost is really good with structured data on classification and regression predictive modeling problems. Moreover, this is a well-known algorithm with great support, so it's easy to understand and iterate over different approaches.

XGBoost implements the gradient boosting decision tree algorithm. The implementation of XGBoost give us quite advanced features for model tuning, computing environments and algorithm enhancement.

Document how you assess your models performance

The metric I used is RMSE. The root-mean-squared error is a measure of how well the model performed. It archive this by measuring difference betweeen predicted values and the actual values.

It is important to pay attention to train-rmse and test-rmse. The RMSE should be close for both the training data and the testing data. If RMSE for testing data is higher than the training data there are high possibilities that the model overfit.

Discuss any limitations or caveats of the model which might be an issue in implementing it

In order to improve the results I drop all observations with tip_amount higher than fifteen because most passengers don't give a tip higher than that value. So, when I tested without this limitation the model performed worse.

Another limitation is the hardware/time available:

  • Playing with the features and the hyperparamters we can archive a better result.
  • Also, a bigger dataset (maybe the entire year) would be great for the performance.

Discuss how you might improve your model going forward

If we delete the previous limitations we can improve the model's performance. Also, styding the feature importance and tuning them we can get better results. Moreover, we can test with other algorithms and compare the performance.

Also, we can binning the target ('tip_amount'). If the company doesn't need high precision we can transform this continuous variable to categorical in order to change the problem from regression to classification getting better results.

Discuss how you might turn this model in to an API the company can use

Depending on the complexity we want there are some options:

  • Some cloud providers offer tools that are ready to solve this problem: AWS SageMaker, Azure ML... Each of them has limitations that it's important to study before take a decision.
  • If we want a custom architecture we can use, for example, a EC2 instance (with auto-scaling depending on the use) controlled by a Lambda. We dockerize the train and the prediction and deploy them. For the API there are several options like using Flask (very easy and fast to develop) or more complex framework like Django. With the model trained and saved we have to request the predictions with the entry parameters.
